# AI Builder Tool Executor (`lib/ai/tool-executor.ts`)

## Core Rule — Tool Behavior Must Mirror the Panel

Every executor function must write to exactly the same place as the builder's right-side panel control for that property. The panel's `patchStyle` path now calls `styleToClassName` before saving, so pixel inputs are stored as arbitrary-value Tailwind classes (e.g. `pt-[16px]`). The tool must do the same — write to `props.className`, never to `style.*` for pixel inputs.

See `ai-builder-knowledge.mdc` for the full alignment philosophy and audit process.

---

## Style mechanism — `set_style` + focused companions

Most visual styling flows through **`set_style`**, which mirrors the Design panel: it merges arbitrary-value Tailwind into `props.className`, clears conflicting `props.style` keys for the same axis, and uses the same subgraph helpers the granular-era tools used. Prefer **`set_style`** for padding, margin, typography (incl. font size px), border radius/width, position inset, shadows, colors, etc. **`set_layout`** remains the dedicated tool for flex direction / justify / align / gap (and related layout width helpers).

**Do not reintroduce** removed aliases (`set_typography`, `set_spacing`, `set_position`, `set_class`, `set_grid`, …) — they are folded into `set_style` / `set_layout` / `set_background` / `set_animation`.

### Inline style vs `className` (still applies inside `set_style`)

**`props.className`:** pixel and token utilities the panel stores as classes (`pt-[Npx]`, `text-[Npx]`, `rounded-[Npx]`, `top-[Npx]`, colors as `text-[…]` / `bg-[…]`, etc.). Strip the matching `props.style` keys when writing the class side.

**`props.style` exceptions** (panel reads these directly or they lack a single class):
- `transform` for **rotation** (`rotate(Ndeg)`)
- **`opacity`** (0–1 float) — also exposed as `set_opacity`
- **`translateX` / `translateY`** (builder-specific; combined at render time with rotation)
- Exact **width/height** strings when the panel uses `patchStyle` for W/H (non–Image nodes): executor may double-write class + style so stale defaults do not win

At render time, `classToInlineStyle()` in `lib/sdui/renderer.tsx` converts arbitrary-value classes from JSON when NativeWind did not see them at build time.

---

## Responsive `breakpoint` parameter

When a write tool accepts **`breakpoint`** (`'laptop' | 'tablet' | 'mobile'`), targeted keys must go under **`node.responsive[breakpoint].…`** (for style-like fields, typically `styles.<cssProp>` or the panel’s `patchResponsive` paths) instead of mutating the base node. When `breakpoint` is omitted, writes apply to the **base** node (desktop / default).

`set_responsive_override` / `clear_responsive_override` are the explicit escape hatch when you need fine-grained control. The Design tab’s blue breakpoint pill UX corresponds to these override slots.

